Joining the indnames file to the data to put names to the industry codes

indnames <- read.csv('indnames.csv', header = TRUE)

data <- left_join(x = data, y = indnames, by = c('IND' = 'ind'))

data <- data %>%
  relocate(indname, .after = IND)

Adding a binary variable that is 0 before covid and 1 after/during covid

# combining year and month into one column called 'date'
data <- data %>%
  relocate(MONTH, .after = YEAR)

data <- data %>%
  mutate(date = paste0(YEAR, '-', MONTH, '-01')) %>%
  mutate(date = ymd(date)) %>%
  relocate(date, .after = MONTH)


# creating the binary variable 
data$covid <- ifelse(data$date >= '2020-03-01', 1, 0)

data <- data %>%
  relocate(covid, .after = date)


# checking to make sure its right
grouped_dates <- data %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarise(mean(covid))

Analysis Write Up

For this project, we are taking on the role of a business analyst for a retail firm. We are aware of our own performance in weathering the pandemic but have been tasked with analyzing how the rest of the retail industry is doing, along with other industries in the economy. Using the IPUMS release of the Current Population Survey, we have compiled an analysis using employment data. We used employment data as opposed to revenue data because factors like government aid and stimuli may skew the results.

Q1: How has COVID affected the health of the retail industry, as measured by employment? In order to observe how retail has fared in the wake of the pandemic, we first had to establish when the pandemic started in order to incorporate a before and after time period into our model. To do this, we first incorporated the month and year variables into their own variable titled date. Then, as a group, we made the assumption that the covid pandemic started in the month of March 2020. We created a binary variable that is 1 when the date is greater than or equal to 2020-03-01, and a 0 for anything before then. This allows us to be able to quantify the association of the start of the covid pandemic on whatever outcome variable we choose when running a regression. Next, we had to prepare our outcome variable. Because the employment variable was numerically coded corresponding to different types of employment/unemployment (not in labor force, employed and skilled, employed and unskilled, armed forces, etc.), we had to create a binary variable that simply indicated employed or not. With this new binary variable titled employed, we can now see how the start of the pandemic was associated with a change in the probability of being employed because our outcome variable is binary. Our ensuing regression will be a linear probability model. Within this analysis, we are assuming that the COVID 19 pandemic began in the month of March 2020. Additionally, we are assuming that there is only one type of employment and one type of unemployment. In other words, you are either employed or not in this analysis. We regressed employed on covid and exported the summary with digits = 3. The resultant table shows an intercept of 0.956, and a coefficient of -0.026 on the covid variable, with a standard error of 0.001, making it significant at an alpha of 0.001. Interpreting these results, we can say that prior to COVID, the employment rate (or more specifically, the percentage probability of being employed) was 95.6%. Following covid, when the covid variable is now a 1, we see a -0.026 or 2.6 percentage point decrease in the probability of being employed. This tells us that after the start of the pandemic, employment probability decreased in the retail sector by a statistically significant amount. This result is clearly identifiable from our regression summary table, but it is also relatively obvious. In order to actually see how the retail industry fared against other industries, we need to expand our analysis.

Q2: How has retail fared relative to other industries? For Question 2, we performed three different difference-in-difference analyses in order to identify how the retail industry has fared relative to other industries. Since we are looking for a change over time, we believed that the difference-in-difference method would provide the best method of closing back doors that shift over time. While difference-in-difference research designs typically have a controlled group and treated group, the data, in this case, does not have a controlled group. Instead, we used Retail Industry as the treated group and non-Retail Industries as the controlled group. While all industries have been impacted by COVID-19, this allows us to look at the employment of Retail and non-Retail Industries before and after the start of COVID-19. Using the difference-in-difference method, we analyzed the likelihood of being employed by the retail industry (treatment group) rather than non-retail industries (controlled group). Prior to the start of COVID-19, the effect of working in the retail industry is associated with approximately 1.2 percentage points lower in the probability of being employed relative to being employed in a non-retail industry. After the start of COVID-19, there is a 0.2 percentage point higher likelihood for people to be employed in the retail industry relative to being employed in a non-retail industry. For this analysis to be considered accurate, we need to assume that there is no uncontrolled endogenous variation across 2019 to 2021. This assumption is also known as parallel trends. In order to account for this, we can look to see if prior trends are the same for retail and non-retail industries. Based on the graph, we do not see any clear trends that would indicate there are other factors affecting our graph.

Q3: Retail needs to worry about who has money to spend - what has changed about who is working and earning money? When considering the impacts both before and after the start of COVID-19, our group is interested in understanding which demographics have money to spend and what changes have occurred across demographics in who spends this money. Our assumption is that the people that have money are the ones that are employed. We selected age, race, and the highest level of education as part of our analysis of the impact these factors have on employment both before and after the start of COVID-19. Age Regression Analysis The Age Regression model is an analysis of the effect of being in a certain age bin during the COVID-19 pandemic has on a persons probability to be employed relative to other age ranges. We grouped the ages into teens, 20s, 30s, 40s, 50s, 60s, and 70s. We decided to make the 20s age group our baseline intercept value, and are focusing on the coefficient for the interaction between level of education and COVID-19. Before the start of the pandemic, the effect of being in your 30s, 40s, 50s, 60s, or 70s is associated with at least 2.1 percentage points higher in the probability of being employed relative to being in your 20s. The effect of being in your 50s before the start of the pandemic has the highest probability of being employed relative to being in your 20s with an association of approximately 2.7 percentage points. Before the start of the pandemic, the effect of being a teen is associated with approximately 6.2 percentage points lower in the probability of being employed relative to being in your 20s. The teen age group had the lowest probability of being employed. After the start of the pandemic, the effect of being in your 30s, 40s, 50s, 60s, or 70s is associated with at least 0.9 percentage points higher in the probability of being employed relative to being in your 20s. The effect of being in your 40s after the start of the pandemic has the highest probability of being employed relative to being in your 20s with an association of approximately 1.2 percentage points. After the start of the pandemic, the effect of being a teen is associated with approximately 0.9 percentage points lower in the probability of being employed relative to being in your 20s. The teen age group had the lowest probability of being employed again. After the pandemic, people in their 40s have the highest probability of being employed relative to people in their 20s, out of all the age groups we looked at. The teen age group had the lowest probability of being employed both before and after the pandemic. Therefore, the retail industry should focus its marketing efforts on people in their 40s. They may also choose to market towards people in their 30s and 50s, the age groups with the next highest probability of being employed compared to people in their 20s. Race Regression Analysis The Race Regression analysis determines the effect of being of a specific race(s) during COVID-19 has on a persons probability of being employed relative to having another race(s). In this regression analysis, we are focusing on the coefficient for the interaction between race(s) and COVID-19. This allows us to measure the effect of a persons race(s) on the probability of being employed relative to being White. Before the start of the pandemic, the effect of being Asian is associated with approximately 0.5 percentage points higher in the probability of being employed relative to being White. Asians were the only race who had a higher probability of being employed relative to being White. Before the start of the pandemic, the effect of being American Indian, Black, Hawaiian/Pacific Islander, or having a mix of multiple races are associated with approximately at least 0.5 percentage points lower in the probability of being employed relative to being White. After the start of the pandemic, the effect of being American Indian, Asian, Black, Hawaiian/Pacific Islander, or having a mix of multiple races are associated with approximately at least 0.3 percentage points lower in the probability of being employed relative to being White. People who are White have had the highest probability of being employed. Before the pandemic, Asians had a higher probability of being employed and should have been retail companies targeted market. However, the effect of being Asian after the start of the pandemic is associated with 0.3 percentage points lower in the probability of being employed relative to being White. Thus, retail companies should shift their marketing efforts towards White people as they have a higher probability of being employed which implies they have money to spend. Education Completion Regression Analysis Our Education Completion Regression Analysis looks at the probability of being employed based on the level of education you have completed. We decided to make completion of high school our baseline intercept value, and are focusing on the coefficient for the interaction between level of education and COVID-19. Our Before the start of the pandemic, the higher your education level, the more likely you are to be employed. For example, having a Bachelors degree is associated with approximately a 2.4 percentage point increase in the probability of being employed, and only completing some high school is associated with approximately a 2.6 percentage point decrease in the probability of being employed. After the start of the pandemic, the new post-Covid baseline probability of being employed is associated with a 3.5 percentage point decrease in the original baseline probability of being employed. The trend of having a higher level of education being associated with a higher probability of being employed also holds true after Covid, except for those who have only completed some college but not earned a degree they are no more likely to be employed than someone who has only earned a high school diploma.

Overall, after the pandemic, the retail industry should target their sales towards White people in their 40s who have Doctorate or Professional school degrees if they want to target those who are working and earning money.
